WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.569 --> 00:00:06.970
bjbj 2011-09-12_wasteland [0:00:04] Martha
Minow: Good afternoon. If you don t have a

00:00:06.970 --> 00:00:17.060
seat, please do take one. It is an enormous
pleasure for me to welcome you all here today

00:00:17.060 --> 00:00:22.980
to this special event. I m Dean Martha Minow
here at Harvard Law School. A half century

00:00:22.980 --> 00:00:30.920
ago, the 35-year-old federal regulator of
an agency most people had never heard of woke

00:00:30.920 --> 00:00:38.640
up the public with a searing speech that to
this day is studied in rhetoric courses. It

00:00:38.640 --> 00:00:46.610
s used in headlines. I happen to know it s
used on a LSAT reading comprehension test

00:00:46.610 --> 00:00:54.520
and it is used in persistent assessments of
how communications technology affects entertainment

00:00:54.520 --> 00:01:02.530
and news, culture and democracy. In 1961,
Newton Minow, appointed by President John

00:01:02.530 --> 00:01:07.690
F. Kennedy to chair the Federal Communications
Commission told the National Association of

00:01:07.690 --> 00:01:15.640
Broadcasters, When television is good, nothing,
not the theater, not the magazines or newspapers,

00:01:15.640 --> 00:01:23.110
nothing is better. But when television is
bad, nothing is worse. I invite each of you

00:01:23.110 --> 00:01:28.799
to sit down in front of your television set
when you station goes on the air and stay

00:01:28.799 --> 00:01:37.510
there for a day without a book, without a
magazine, without a newspaper, without a profit

00:01:37.510 --> 00:01:43.729
and loss sheet or a rating book to distract
you. Keep your eyes glued to that set until

00:01:43.729 --> 00:01:49.940
the station signs off. And here it comes,
I can assure you that what you will observe

00:01:49.940 --> 00:01:58.560
is a vast wasteland, borrowing from T.S. Eliot
s great poem. Newton Minow challenged American

00:01:58.560 --> 00:02:04.409
broadcasters actually to watch the shows that
they were putting out on the public air waves,

00:02:04.409 --> 00:02:10.680
the game shows, the violence, the boredom;
and he shocked a complacent industry. He called

00:02:10.680 --> 00:02:18.120
for imagination, excellence and creativity.
Fifty years later, we bring him here to meet

00:02:18.120 --> 00:02:24.299
with the amazingly imaginative, excellent
and creative individuals who will participate

00:02:24.299 --> 00:02:30.120
in today s program. They include remarkable
people from the Berkman Center for Internet

00:02:30.120 --> 00:02:34.890
and Society which is rooted here in the law
school while reaching the university and the

00:02:34.890 --> 00:02:40.950
world, extraordinary journalists who will
explore with us where we are now, a vaster

00:02:40.950 --> 00:02:46.100
wasteland or a new greatness when it comes
to entertainment and news, policy makers,

00:02:46.100 --> 00:02:53.850
other former regulators, imaginative theorists.
You are in for a treat, those of you who are

00:02:53.850 --> 00:02:59.130
here. I want to give my personal thanks to
the participants from the Berkman Center,

00:02:59.130 --> 00:03:04.980
John Palfrey, Terry Fisher, Yochai Benkler,
Jonathan Zittrain, Urs Gasser and so many

00:03:04.980 --> 00:03:11.160
others who made this event happen. You are
all stars and I give special thanks to all

00:03:11.160 --> 00:03:18.320
of you. m so pleased also to welcome Ann Marie
Lipinski here and also to Harvard, now the

00:03:18.320 --> 00:03:23.250
head of the Nieman Foundation which co-sponsors
this event. She s a Pulitzer Prize winning

00:03:23.250 --> 00:03:28.320
journalist and active participant in constructing
new models of non-profit newsgathering and

00:03:28.320 --> 00:03:33.650
distribution and she brings the eye of a writer,
the judgment of an editor and the wisdom of

00:03:33.650 --> 00:03:39.400
someone who has survived the tumult in both
the newspaper business and the academic world.

00:03:39.400 --> 00:03:45.160
Jonathan Alter will also be here. He has been
described as the most astute political observer

00:03:45.160 --> 00:03:49.910
in his generation. He too an award-winning
and best-selling author, now at Bloomberg

00:03:49.910 --> 00:03:59.060
News after 28 years at Newsweek and on Twitter
I happen to know personally. Susan Crawford,

00:03:59.060 --> 00:04:05.790
expert on internet governance and information
regulation. Perry Hewitt, expert on the digital

00:04:05.790 --> 00:04:14.220
world and social networking. Nicholas Negroponte,
the remarkable, inspiring figure from the

00:04:14.220 --> 00:04:23.430
MIT Media Lab and the One Laptop per Child
initiative. Tim Wu, whose studies of information

00:04:23.430 --> 00:04:32.480
empires have rocked the world anew. Ellen
Goodman, information analyst par excellence.

00:04:32.480 --> 00:04:37.230
I am so thrilled you re all here and I promise
I will sit down in a second so the discussion

00:04:37.230 --> 00:04:43.170
really starts but I do have a point of personal
privilege which takes me back to Newton Minow.

00:04:43.170 --> 00:04:48.410
A veteran of World War Two, Minow learned
the significance of global communication during

00:04:48.410 --> 00:04:54.360
his service in the China Burma India Theater
during that war. He built a career spanning

00:04:54.360 --> 00:05:00.361
law, politics, the academy and business while
helping to build and criticize the [0:05:00]

00:05:00.361 --> 00:05:05.760
news communication world. He has chaired the
Public Broadcasting Service. He helped to

00:05:05.760 --> 00:05:11.630
fund Sesame Street. He has advised networks
and cable companies. He s an architect and

00:05:11.630 --> 00:05:16.960
statesman of the presidential debates televised
and video streamed on the internet in this

00:05:16.960 --> 00:05:22.640
country for decades, of counsel to the law
firm Sidley Austin Brown and Wood, long time

00:05:22.640 --> 00:05:27.480
university professor at Northwestern University.
He is the husband of Jo Minow who is here

00:05:27.480 --> 00:05:35.840
today and they are my beloved parents. T.S.
Eliot who gave dad the phrase vast wasteland

00:05:35.840 --> 00:05:42.690
also said, It is in fact a part of the function
of education to help us to escape, not from

00:05:42.690 --> 00:05:48.540
our own time for we are bound by that, but
from the intellectual and emotional limitations

00:05:48.540 --> 00:05:53.970
of our time. I look forward to this session
