here today, I hadn t focused on the date.
I didn t realize it was going to be one day

00:07:49.930 --> 00:07:57.830
after 9/11 and like all of you, yesterday
was a very emotional one for me. Our firms

00:07:57.830 --> 00:08:06.410
and New York office was in the World Trade
Center. We had 677 people there and when it

00:08:06.410 --> 00:08:14.570
was all over, the office manager got everyone
to the first floor and we said, Fortunately,

00:08:14.570 --> 00:08:20.139
we only lost one person, a receptionist who
somehow disappeared after they got to the

00:08:20.139 --> 00:08:27.320
first floor. Today, we say, Unfortunately
we lost one person. Also [0:08:26] [Indiscernible]

00:08:27.320 --> 00:08:33.789
was a member of the board of directors of
the Aon Corporation which had 900 people in

00:08:33.789 --> 00:08:45.190
the building and lost 177; and yesterday,
I read in the Chicago Tribune at home an interview

00:08:45.190 --> 00:08:53.570
with the former CEO of Aon who said he was
brought to tears this week when he got two

00:08:53.570 --> 00:09:02.290
letters. One from a freshman at Columbia University,
one from a freshman at Tufts thanking Aon

00:09:02.290 --> 00:09:11.360
for making it possible to have scholarships
for all the children of those who died there.

00:09:11.360 --> 00:09:17.780
So it s something really to think about. In
terms of communications, do you realize that

00:09:17.780 --> 00:09:31.190
10 years ago there was no YouTube video? Ten
years ago, there were no cameras and cell

00:09:31.190 --> 00:09:38.230
phones. Ten years ago, there were no tweets.
There was no Twitter. That was 10 years ago.

00:09:38.230 --> 00:09:46.140
Then let s talk about 50 years ago when most
of you were not even born. What was it like

00:09:46.140 --> 00:09:55.290
for me as a young person to be sent by President
Kennedy to the Federal Communications Commission?

00:09:55.290 --> 00:10:06.480
At that time, phone calls went by wire. [0:10:00]
Broadcasting went through the air. Today,

00:10:06.480 --> 00:10:13.620
as Professor Negroponte has pointed out, something
we should have all seen, until he observed

00:10:13.620 --> 00:10:20.850
it himself, most phone calls go through the
air and most people get their television service

00:10:20.850 --> 00:10:29.150
either by wire or by satellite. It had been
a fundamental basic transformation in the

00:10:29.150 --> 00:10:35.480
world of communications and yet, there have
been very little thinking about what that

00:10:35.480 --> 00:10:44.380
really means. In 1961, there were two and
a half television networks. There was one

00:10:44.380 --> 00:10:54.390
telephone company. There were no personal
computers. There was no public television.

00:10:54.390 --> 00:11:05.080
There was no public radio. FM radio was dormant.
Cable was fledgling. There was no internet

00:11:05.080 --> 00:11:12.100
and usually, there was only one television
set in a home. It was a small black and white

00:11:12.100 --> 00:11:20.550
set and the entire family watched the same
program at the same time. Audience was passive.

00:11:20.550 --> 00:11:30.370
They listened or watched silently. There were
scandals in the broadcasting industry, bad

00:11:30.370 --> 00:11:38.800
scandals in the 50s involving payola, involving
scams of various kinds. There were scandals

00:11:38.800 --> 00:11:46.050
at the FCC. President Kennedy s predecessor,
President Eisenhower, had to fire the chairman

00:11:46.050 --> 00:11:52.380
of the FCC for improper conduct. [0:11:49]
[Indiscernible] the industry and the agency

00:11:52.380 --> 00:12:02.500
were both in bad trouble. On May 5th of that
year, there was a great triumph, the successful

00:12:02.500 --> 00:12:11.460
launch of the first American in space, Commander
Alan Shepard. On May 8th, Shepard returned

00:12:11.460 --> 00:12:18.730
from space and he came to see President Kennedy
in his office and they were then going to

00:12:18.730 --> 00:12:24.720
go to congress. On the same day, President
Kennedy was to speak to the National Association

00:12:24.720 --> 00:12:32.740
of Broadcasters and he had called and invited
me to ride with him to his speech and I was

00:12:32.740 --> 00:12:39.690
to meet him outside the Oval Office. I was
waiting for him. President Kennedy came out

00:12:39.690 --> 00:12:44.440
and he said, Newt. He said, The Shepards are
here. He said, What do you think about taking

00:12:44.440 --> 00:12:50.660
them to the broadcasters convention? I said,
That would be perfect. That would mean everything.

00:12:50.660 --> 00:12:55.381
He said, Well, and wait a minute. He said,
Let me go in and arrange it and I ll come

00:12:55.381 --> 00:13:02.141
back and I ll get you. He came back out and
he said, OK, it s all set. Come with me though.

00:13:02.141 --> 00:13:08.590
I want to change my shirt. So he took me upstairs
to the living quarters of the White House

00:13:08.590 --> 00:13:13.810
and even though I had known the president
before, I was scared to death. Here I was

00:13:13.810 --> 00:13:19.339
with the president of the United States, watching
him change his shirt and he said to me he

00:13:19.339 --> 00:13:26.730
said, What do you think I should say to the
broadcasters? as if he hadn t given it any

00:13:26.730 --> 00:13:33.100
thought before; and I said, I think you ought
to tell them the difference between a free

00:13:33.100 --> 00:13:40.250
society and a closed society. The Soviets
sent people into space but you really never

00:13:40.250 --> 00:13:46.560
know if it was successful or it wasn t. There
was no radio and television there to cover

00:13:46.560 --> 00:13:54.490
it but in our country, we let everybody see
and hear what was going on. So you ought to

00:13:54.490 --> 00:14:00.760
talk about what the contribution broadcasting
made to our citizens to understand this new

00:14:00.760 --> 00:14:05.810
world. The president didn t say anything.
He didn t say that s good or that s bad. He

00:14:05.810 --> 00:14:11.500
finished changing his shirt. We went downstairs
and took me in the Oval Office and there were

00:14:11.500 --> 00:14:16.649
Commander Shepard and his wife and there was
Vice President Johnson. We were all going

00:14:16.649 --> 00:14:21.089
to go together and we went, walked out to
the driveway and I thought I would get in

00:14:21.089 --> 00:14:25.220
the second car because now we had the Shepards
and the vice president. The president says,

00:14:25.220 --> 00:14:30.180
No, no, no. He says, Newt, come on. Just get
in the jump seat. He said, Lyndon, you get

00:14:30.180 --> 00:14:36.250
in the other jump seat, and he put the Shepards
in the backseat with himself; and we drove

00:14:36.250 --> 00:14:42.960
through Rock Creek Park up to what was then
called the Wardman Park Hotel. It s now called

00:14:42.960 --> 00:14:46.830
the Sheraton Park Hotel and the president
was in a very ebullient mood. This was after

00:14:46.830 --> 00:14:51.850
the failure of the Bay of Pigs. Here is something
that had gone right. We had a success. We

00:14:51.850 --> 00:14:58.780
were catching up with the Russians so he slapped
Lyndon on the shoulder and he said, Lyndon,

00:14:58.780 --> 00:15:04.820
you are the chairman of the [0:15:00] National
Space Council, and the vice president said,

00:15:04.820 --> 00:15:09.839
Yes. The president said, Yes, but nobody knows
that Lyndon. But he said, I guarantee you,

00:15:09.839 --> 00:15:14.300
Lyndon. If this had been a failure, if that
space shot had been a failure, I would have

00:15:14.300 --> 00:15:25.221
seen to it that everybody [Laughter] Newton
Minow: Lyndon didn t laugh and I [Laughter]

00:15:25.221 --> 00:15:28.720
Newton Minow: But I was next to him at the
other jump seat and unfortunately, I have

00:15:28.720 --> 00:15:34.570
a big mouth. I couldn t resist it. So I said,
Mr. President. I said, If it had been a failure,

00:15:34.570 --> 00:15:44.800
the vice president would have been the next
astronaut. [Laughter] Newt Minow: Which the

00:15:44.800 --> 00:15:50.370
vice president didn t think was very funny
either. [Laughter] Newt Minow: When we got

00:15:50.370 --> 00:15:57.529
there, the president gave a three-minute,
perfectly-timed, a perfectly-phrased speech

00:15:57.529 --> 00:16:04.300
about the difference between a free society
and a closed society, about how broadcasting

00:16:04.300 --> 00:16:11.060
had allowed every American to see what was
going on. He got a standing ovation. The next

00:16:11.060 --> 00:16:18.970
day, I came to speak and I think the broadcaster
wished I had changed my shirt because there

00:16:18.970 --> 00:16:32.370
was no standing ovation. Now why did I give
that speech? Television had become, in 1961,

00:16:32.370 --> 00:16:38.459
the dominant form of communication in our
country. Everybody could afford it and that

00:16:38.459 --> 00:16:46.370
was most people had a television set. The
Kennedy-Nixon debate on television in 1960

00:16:46.370 --> 00:16:52.861
had, in my opinion and in the opinion of President
Kennedy, decided the election. Television

00:16:52.861 --> 00:16:58.740
had become extremely important but there had
been very little discussion or debate in the

00:16:58.740 --> 00:17:07.750
country about what that meant in terms of
public responsibility, public interest and

00:17:07.750 --> 00:17:14.489
I was determined even though I knew that my
speech would not be welcomed. My favorite

00:17:14.489 --> 00:17:20.679
response was from a man named Sherwood Schwartz
who was the producer of a program called Gilligan

00:17:20.679 --> 00:17:28.459
s Island. He sent me a message because he
named the sinking ship after me, the S.S.

00:17:28.459 --> 00:17:38.940
Minnow. [Laughter] Newt Minow: But I knew
what I was getting into and now that was 50

00:17:38.940 --> 00:17:46.690
years ago and what I decided the government
s role should be and this is what I hope we

00:17:46.690 --> 00:17:54.049
ll get into here. The government s role, I
felt, was to expand choice, to open up new

00:17:54.049 --> 00:17:59.529
channels. We opened up the UHF channels. We
asked congress to pass a bill that required

00:17:59.529 --> 00:18:05.470
that every television set could tune into
a UHF channel which quintupled the number

00:18:05.470 --> 00:18:14.860
of television channels. We opened up cable.
Satellites were discovered. President Kennedy

00:18:14.860 --> 00:18:20.020
took me on a tour of the space program and
he said to me, Why do you think these communication

00:18:20.020 --> 00:18:25.350
satellites are so important? And I said, Mr.
President, they re more important than sending

00:18:25.350 --> 00:18:31.669
a man into space. He said, Why is that? I
said, Communication satellites will send ideas

00:18:31.669 --> 00:18:39.140
into space and ideas last longer than people.
Communication satellites have fundamentally

00:18:39.140 --> 00:18:46.340
changed we can see what s going on all over
the world and they can see us. All the things

00:18:46.340 --> 00:18:52.179
that are happening in the Middle East, many
people believe, are really caused by the explosion

00:18:52.179 --> 00:19:00.110
in satellite communication. I felt it was
a disgrace that we had no public television.

00:19:00.110 --> 00:19:07.149
I came to the FCC from Chicago where we had
channel 11, a public station. President Kennedy

00:19:07.149 --> 00:19:13.630
came from Boston where there was WGBH. In
our ignorance, we thought every city had a

00:19:13.630 --> 00:19:18.460
public television station. We found out there
was none in New York City, the largest city

00:19:18.460 --> 00:19:23.980
in the country. There was none in Los Angeles,
the second largest city in the country. There

00:19:23.980 --> 00:19:29.340
was none in Washington D.C., the nation s
capital. So we decided something had to be

00:19:29.340 --> 00:19:36.369
done about that and we ve succeeded. Congress
passed the first legislation that helped create

00:19:36.369 --> 00:19:45.830
public television. We got stations going in
New York and Los Angeles and Washington and

00:19:45.830 --> 00:19:52.049
I felt that after two years, I was going broke.
Martha was and her sisters. Martha was six

00:19:52.049 --> 00:20:02.019
years old. Her sisters were [Laughter] Newt
Minow: [0:20:00] Her older and younger sisters.

00:20:02.019 --> 00:20:06.830
I was I couldn t afford it anymore so I had
promised President Kennedy I would be there

00:20:06.830 --> 00:20:12.799
for two years. Two years to the day, I asked
for an appointment to see him. I walked in.

00:20:12.799 --> 00:20:17.409
The president said, re the only guy I brought
here who never asked to see me. I know what

00:20:17.409 --> 00:20:21.320
you want. You want to go home. I said, That
s right, Mr. President. I can t afford it.

00:20:21.320 --> 00:20:27.739
He says, Are you sure you don t want another
job? I said, So I left but I felt I had accomplished

00:20:27.739 --> 00:20:38.429
a lot. After I left the government, I have
