Negroponte: That s a real compliment. I sort

01:38:37.010 --> 01:38:42.389
of come from a slightly different world where
we spend less time reflecting and more time

01:38:42.389 --> 01:38:49.190
inventing. So I m a little bit of an interloper
here but by chance when I founded the Media

01:38:49.190 --> 01:38:54.229
Lab, my partner was in the White House with
you, Newt. It was Jerry Wiesner and he told

01:38:54.229 --> 01:39:02.179
me a story very early on when I first got
to know in the 70s about how he brought Vladimir

01:39:02.179 --> 01:39:05.420
s work into the White House. I don t know
if you remember the name but Vladimir Sworkin

01:39:05.420 --> 01:39:11.560
is generally credited with inventing television.
It was a Saturday and Jerry sent his work

01:39:11.560 --> 01:39:16.550
and then I won t try and imitate Sworkin s
but it was a very heavy German accent. He

01:39:16.550 --> 01:39:21.039
said, Have you ever met the president? He
said, He said, Well, let s go see if he s

01:39:21.039 --> 01:39:25.439
in his office, and he was there and [01:39:22]
[Indiscernible]. It was a Saturday afternoon

01:39:25.439 --> 01:39:32.760
and he says, Mr. President, I want you to
meet the man who got you elected. Apparently,

01:39:32.760 --> 01:39:38.639
Kennedy said, Oh, you know, how is that? and
he said, This is the man who invented television.

01:39:38.639 --> 01:39:45.050
Apparently, Kennedy said, Oh my goodness.
You did such a wonderful thing, and so on.

01:39:45.050 --> 01:39:50.280
As Jerry sort of tells that it s working,
looks at him and says, Mr. President, have

01:39:50.280 --> 01:39:57.230
you looked at television recently? [Laughter]
Nicholas Negroponte: He said, When we invented

01:39:57.230 --> 01:40:01.780
it, we thought we were inventing an educational
[01:40:00] medium. We thought we were inventing

01:40:01.780 --> 01:40:09.219
a medium for the arts, and one of the things
I took away from that story was the difference

01:40:09.219 --> 01:40:14.280
between television and photography. I m going
to use photography as an example. The people

01:40:14.280 --> 01:40:20.170
who invented television were engineers who
then threw it over the wall and various people

01:40:20.170 --> 01:40:27.699
used it. People who invented photography were
photographers and the same people who made

01:40:27.699 --> 01:40:34.070
the creative content invented the medium and
that s what I think is happening in computers.

01:40:34.070 --> 01:40:39.849
That was why we started the Media Lab, to
make a place where the inventors and the creative

01:40:39.849 --> 01:40:45.749
users were the same people; and for 25 years,
we ve been doing that and that s the reason

01:40:45.749 --> 01:40:51.300
why we from those years. Newt Minow: And do
you come out then as an optimist that while

01:40:51.300 --> 01:40:56.429
we are talking and talking policy, you re
out building? Nicholas Negroponte: m well-known

01:40:56.429 --> 01:41:02.820
as being A, unrealistic and B, an optimist
about everything so yes, very much an optimist.

01:41:02.820 --> 01:41:05.849
Jonathan Zittrain: I can t tell you if you
complimented yourself or not but [Laughter]

01:41:05.849 --> 01:41:11.590
Nicholas Negroponte: You haven t been able
to tell much since I was there but yes, I

01:41:11.590 --> 01:41:17.170
m an optimist and I m sort of sometimes so
extremely optimistic that you should, you

01:41:17.170 --> 01:41:22.170
know, not believe me. [Laughter] Jonathan
Zittrain: Which of course makes you far more

01:41:22.170 --> 01:41:27.389
credible. So it s that sort of I mean part
of I think what we ve all been grasping at

01:41:27.389 --> 01:41:35.039
so far is capturing the kind of authenticity
that this medium could allow. Maybe it did,

01:41:35.039 --> 01:41:40.439
maybe it didn t, trying to elicit it from
the medium and trying to achieve the same

01:41:40.439 --> 01:41:46.340
thing today as more and more choices are there
and many of the doors have false ones behind

01:41:46.340 --> 01:41:51.969
them and others may have [01:41:47] [Indiscernible]
that otherwise wouldn t come through. We are

01:41:51.969 --> 01:41:57.050
nearing the end of our time. We haven t even
had a chance to open it up because to sort

01:41:57.050 --> 01:42:05.719
of unpredictable characters because we have
not predictable characters. Predicted characters.

01:42:05.719 --> 01:42:09.499
That didn t sound like a compliment at all.
Jonathan Alter: It didn Jonathan Zittrain:

01:42:09.499 --> 01:42:14.269
m just trying to make Susan s pearls before
swine comment recede but I just failed at

01:42:14.269 --> 01:42:18.790
that too. Female Speaker: You say something
funny, you don t need to be Jonathan Zittrain:

01:42:18.790 --> 01:42:23.559
So I don John, I m just going to call on you
real quick as sort of a proxy, given we have

01:42:23.559 --> 01:42:30.620
so little time though, for those voices that
haven t been organized ahead of time. You

01:42:30.620 --> 01:42:34.969
ve actually had your eye on the Twitter stream
so I hate to have that kind of old CNN moment

01:42:34.969 --> 01:42:39.820
where they re like, So what does so and so
in Baghdad have to say? but I m curious. Is

01:42:39.820 --> 01:42:45.119
there anything different that has been happening
in response to this online that hasn t yet

01:42:45.119 --> 01:42:48.729
found its way to the floor here? John Palfrey:
I was struck that you were actually RT-ing

01:42:48.729 --> 01:42:53.040
the comment by Susan Crawford about pearls
before swine in real time but Jonathan Zittrain:

01:42:53.040 --> 01:42:55.969
Pearls before swine John Palfrey: Yes. That
s even better, right? Pearls before swine.

01:42:55.969 --> 01:43:01.880
There s a huge amount of Twitter traffic on
here. A lot of it actually is of course reflecting

01:43:01.880 --> 01:43:08.209
on things happening in the room but also some
wondering what Chairman Minow makes of 140

01:43:08.209 --> 01:43:13.739
characters in this sort of short form discussions
on Twitter. So I don t know if there s a way

01:43:13.739 --> 01:43:18.969
that this could be one last question back
to the great man but the social media that

01:43:18.969 --> 01:43:21.900
has Jonathan Zittrain: Yes. John Palfrey:
been in the back channel of this room and

01:43:21.900 --> 01:43:27.679
other rooms that are watching the webcast
are kind of wondering about real time feedback

01:43:27.679 --> 01:43:31.130
from you. Jonathan Zittrain: So the last question,
Twitter, threat or menace? [Laughter] Newt

01:43:31.130 --> 01:43:41.099
Minow: Well, I would like to make one comment.
I think the more communication, the better.

01:43:41.099 --> 01:43:47.920
I would like to thank you for inviting me
today. Fifty years, it s hard to believe you

01:43:47.920 --> 01:43:58.139
re still thinking about a speech 50 years
ago. Jonathan who is in my view the Scotty

01:43:58.139 --> 01:44:06.110
Reston of today s generation of political
journalists, Ann Marie who has not only won

01:44:06.110 --> 01:44:12.519
a Pulitzer but won the admiration of everybody
in her field and we re glad she s here at

01:44:12.519 --> 01:44:18.599
Harvard. Yochai, I ve never met you before
today but I read your work and I admire it

01:44:18.599 --> 01:44:26.639
and I m delighted that I was invited here
today. I see somebody here who will one day

01:44:26.639 --> 01:44:35.829
be chairman of the FCC and when that happens,
I hope you will remember that the two words

01:44:35.829 --> 01:44:47.709
in that statute, the public interest, still
have a meaning which too often is easily forgotten.

01:44:47.709 --> 01:44:53.739
Jonathan Zittrain: I am pleased then to turn
the proceedings, with you having successfully

01:44:53.739 --> 01:44:57.535
not answered the Twitter question, over to
our chairman, Terry Fisher, [01:45:00] to

01:44:57.535 --> 01:45:14.059
bring us in for a landing. Terry. Terry Fisher:
So, as many people have rightly pointed out

01:45:14.059 --> 01:45:23.280
some extraordinarily rich and diverse discussion,
impossible to summarize. So instead of making

01:45:23.280 --> 01:45:32.539
that attempt, I thought I would try to identify
a few of the themes upon which there seems

01:45:32.539 --> 01:45:42.429
to be agreement in the room and a few comments
on them. So, it strikes me that the conversation

01:45:42.429 --> 01:45:50.790
has revealed the extent to which technology
and it should be emphasized. Social practices

01:45:50.790 --> 01:45:57.670
that are enabled but not dictated by those
technologies have are in the process of corroding

01:45:57.670 --> 01:46:04.010
some fundamental divides that have shaped
and structured information, entertainment

01:46:04.010 --> 01:46:09.249
and our senses ourselves. So, here are the
divides, as I say, just picking up on themes

01:46:09.249 --> 01:46:15.350
that emerged in the discussions. First is
that division between public and private,

01:46:15.350 --> 01:46:23.239
the reversal of the trend of the 19th century
which was sharp separation of large institutions

01:46:23.239 --> 01:46:28.489
into two discreet categories, governments,
institutions intentionally pursuing the public

01:46:28.489 --> 01:46:34.920
interest on the one hand and private parties
coordinated primarily by the invisible hand

01:46:34.920 --> 01:46:40.889
and nothing more. That division which began
in the early 19th century and hardened by

01:46:40.889 --> 01:46:49.530
1900 is now being reversed and the clearest
manifestation is the emergence of extraordinarily

01:46:49.530 --> 01:46:54.099
powerful new aggregators and channelers of
information of which Google would be the easiest

01:46:54.099 --> 01:46:59.780
example. So in this contest, I would suggest
in response to Ellen. We re not in a post-institutional

01:46:59.780 --> 01:47:07.420
world. It s just the most powerful institutions
are changing and they are arising in between

01:47:07.420 --> 01:47:13.809
the zone of public and private. Other divides
that are deteriorating fast or that are traditional

01:47:13.809 --> 01:47:21.099
divides include that between professional
and amateur, that between speaker and audience,

01:47:21.099 --> 01:47:26.989
that as Virginia suggested between news and
entertainment. Always a fuzzy boundary but

01:47:26.989 --> 01:47:33.429
blurring ever more so now and finally, it
should be emphasized here, the boundary between

01:47:33.429 --> 01:47:39.610
the university and society at large as we
collectively do and should direct our voices

01:47:39.610 --> 01:47:47.559
less at our own communities and more out.
So these changes, the corrosion of all these

01:47:47.559 --> 01:47:56.830
divides have had all of the speakers seem
to be suggesting both huge benefits and huge

01:47:56.830 --> 01:48:03.099
costs. The benefits include the democratization
of the process information and entertainment

01:48:03.099 --> 01:48:11.369
production, the collapse of oligopolies and
the reduction of bias of the story that Ethan

01:48:11.369 --> 01:48:18.199
is working to undermine. An increase in the
amount of depth and potential for accuracy

01:48:18.199 --> 01:48:26.119
exemplified for example by the story of the
Hussein hanging. A dramatic increase in the

01:48:26.119 --> 01:48:32.769
direction to return to one of Newt s original
provocations of a free society as opposed

01:48:32.769 --> 01:48:41.230
to a closed society manifested in the contribution
contested of the internet and new media to

01:48:41.230 --> 01:48:47.059
[01:48:40] [Indiscernible] and the revolutions
sweeping North Africa and finally, the resurrection

01:48:47.059 --> 01:48:55.479
of new kinds of communities. We are bulling
alone less often now. Big benefits, huge benefits.

01:48:55.479 --> 01:48:59.550
At the same time, there are corresponding
costs that have received a lot of attention

01:48:59.550 --> 01:49:08.230
here. They include the fragmentation, the
loss of a coherent culture, the Tower of Babel,

01:49:08.230 --> 01:49:16.280
the threat of sacrificing content, context,
at least if Jonathan is correct, for the majority

01:49:16.280 --> 01:49:26.320
of people and the superficiality of what Ethan
refers to as the special power of video programming.

01:49:26.320 --> 01:49:32.329
So we ve got massive changes underway, partly
technological, partly social, impossible to

01:49:32.329 --> 01:49:39.059
stop with some very large benefits and some
very large costs. So, accepting Newt s invitation

01:49:39.059 --> 01:49:46.340
to look forward, it strikes me that there
are underway a couple of additional advantages

01:49:46.340 --> 01:49:52.510
that have not received too much attention
here and a method that Yochai in his comment

01:49:52.510 --> 01:49:57.719
highlighted of ameliorating the cost. The
benefit that we haven t talked about much

01:49:57.719 --> 01:50:04.349
is the advantage in changing [01:50:00] the
people who contribute to this now democratized

01:50:04.349 --> 01:50:09.679
process of generating information. We focused
on the quality of the stuff they generate

01:50:09.679 --> 01:50:15.489
not on what it does to us as producers. So
this new environment is one in which we are

01:50:15.489 --> 01:50:24.489
collectively with extraordinary breadth, as
John Palfrey has revealed in his work, producers

01:50:24.489 --> 01:50:31.050
of the culture in which we live. We are engaged.
We are no longer primarily passive, one of

01:50:31.050 --> 01:50:39.349
the accusations Newt convincingly made in
the 1960s. Semiotic democracy is in part a

01:50:39.349 --> 01:50:47.110
virtue because of what it does to us. OK,
that s the extra benefit I wanted to emphasize.

01:50:47.110 --> 01:50:54.260
Now, the method of ameliorating the cost that
Yochai touched upon, that he wanted to emphasize,

01:50:54.260 --> 01:51:01.249
is we are seeing and could see more of the
emergence of innovated, distributed models

01:51:01.249 --> 01:51:08.239
for sifting, vetting as you suggested, curating
and organizing information. They include,

01:51:08.239 --> 01:51:13.739
as we have often remarked, Wikipedia. They
often also include in the technological space

01:51:13.739 --> 01:51:20.349
collective sites like Slashdot and then they
include within the universities projects the

01:51:20.349 --> 01:51:25.920
sort exemplified here by digital humanities
pioneered by Jeffrey Schnapp, which for example

01:51:25.920 --> 01:51:31.969
is providing a remarkably deep, new way of
organizing information; some of it video,

01:51:31.969 --> 01:51:38.610
some of it non-video about the Japanese tsunami.
A way of gathering information together and

01:51:38.610 --> 01:51:45.599
making it widely available that television
never achieved and could not achieve. So,

01:51:45.599 --> 01:51:57.150
my hope is that we, focusing on these potentials,
can accept Nicholas spirit of optimism rather

01:51:57.150 --> 01:52:05.079
than pessimism, to see that it is in our power
to inflect, not halt the developments. It

01:52:05.079 --> 01:52:15.999
may be here a heresy in this room that the
FCC is not the prime mover any longer, recognizing

01:52:15.999 --> 01:52:22.969
the rapid emergence and growing power of the
intermediaries and the diminution in opportunities

01:52:22.969 --> 01:52:30.479
for genuine, progressive, regulatory change
at the governmental level. That it is the

01:52:30.479 --> 01:52:36.269
growing intermediaries of which Google is
only the first where the real power locates

01:52:36.269 --> 01:52:43.260
and that s where we should concentrate our
energies and seek ways of moving this environment

01:52:43.260 --> 01:52:49.429
in the direction of the public interest. Jonathan
Zittrain: Terry, you managed to give us a

01:52:49.429 --> 01:52:56.019
perfect synthesis of everything that happened
and to ask us to shake ourselves by the lapels,

01:52:56.019 --> 01:53:05.820
to take up the opportunities that are offered
by this new environment. We now get to eliminate

01:53:05.820 --> 01:53:14.050
the divide between speakers and audience as
we thank our special contributors, our respondents,

01:53:14.050 --> 01:53:21.360
Jonathan, Ann Marie, Yochai and most of all
Newt Minow and in fact, all three Minows.

01:53:21.360 --> 01:53:23.809
We ve learned so much. The School of Minows
Newt Minow: Thank you so much. [Applause]

